http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Observation method is a high-level classification of the method used to make environmental observations. The initial list of methods is based on a subset of NASA's Global Change Master Directory (GCMD) Platforms keyword list (http://gcmd.nasa.gov/learn/keyword_list.html).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The network uses aircraft, balloons, rockets or other airborne instrumentation
The network uses earth observation satellites (for example, LANDSAT, MODIS)
The network uses human assessments or surveys (for example species counts and vegetation canopy cover estimates completed by a botanist, human observation of animal movement).
The network uses in-situ hydrological-based platforms (for example, streamflow gauges, water quality sensors).
The network uses in-situ land-based platforms (for example, weather stations, air monitoring stations, or seismological stations).
The network uses in-situ ocean-based platforms (for example, ships, buoys, or moorings).
The network uses models or data analysis (for example, climate models, soil models, or land surface models).
The network uses navigation platforms (for example, Global Positioning System, NAVSTAR, or GLONASS).
